(a) Given a Known Fixed Point and a Specified Direction: Given that a Line $$l$$ passes through a Fixed Point $$A$$ with Position Vector $$a = a_{1}i + a_{2}j + a_{3}k$$ and that line $$l$$ is parallel to a Specified Direction given by a Direction Vector $$b = b_{1}i + b_{2}j + b_{3}k$$ then a Vector Equation of the Line $$l$$ is given by: $$r = a + \lambda b$$, $$\lambda \in R$$  
;
;(b) Given that a Line $$l$$ passes through Two Fixed Points $$A$$ and $$B$$ with position vectors $$a$$ and $$b$$ respectively, then a direction vector of the line $$l$$ is given by $$\overrightarrow{AB} = b - a$$ or $$\overrightarrow{BA} = a- b$$, thus the Vector Equation of the Line $$l$$ is given by: $$r = a + \lambda (b - a)$$ or $$r = a + \lambda (a - b)$$ or $$r = b + \lambda (b - a)$$ or $$r = b + \lambda (a - b)$$ where $$\lambda \in R$$

